doc.after: Pre-dreadnought battleships are sea-going battleships built between the mid- to late-1880s and 1905, before the launch of HMSÂ Dreadnought.[1] Pre-dreadnoughts replaced the ironclad battleships of the 1870s and 1880s. Built from steel, and protected by hardened steel armour, pre-dreadnought battleships carried a main battery of very heavy guns in barbettes (open or with armored gunhouses) supported by one or more secondary batteries of lighter weapons. They were powered by coal-fuelled triple-expansion steam engines.
